+# SOLUTION
+
+## Root Cause
+
+When an index's properties change (e.g., fill factor, uniqueness, sort order), `MigrationsModelDiffer` generates a `DropIndexOperation` followed by a `CreateIndexOperation` for the same index. `SqlServerMigrationsSqlGenerator` was emitting these as two separate DDL statements: `DROP INDEX ... ON [Table]` followed by `CREATE ... INDEX ... ON [Table]`.
+
+SQL Server supports `CREATE INDEX ... WITH (DROP_EXISTING = ON)` which atomically replaces an existing index. This approach is superior because:
+- The old index remains available to queries while the new one is being built.
+- On large tables this avoids a window where the index is absent.
+- It is a single DDL statement instead of two.
+
+## Change Description
+
+### `src/EFCore.SqlServer/Metadata/Internal/SqlServerAnnotationNames.cs`
+Added `DropExisting = Prefix + "DropExisting"` — a migration-only annotation used to signal the SQL generator that a `CREATE INDEX` statement should include `DROP_EXISTING = ON`.
+
+### `src/EFCore.SqlServer/Migrations/SqlServerMigrationsSqlGenerator.cs`
+**RewriteOperations (post-processing pass):** After the main temporal-table rewriting loop, a backward iteration over the final operations list collapses adjacent `DropIndexOperation` + `CreateIndexOperation` pairs that refer to the same index (same name, table, and schema). When a pair is found and the new index is not a full-text index, vector index, JSON index, or on a memory-optimized table (all cases that use non-standard DDL syntax incompatible with `DROP_EXISTING`), the `DropIndexOperation` is removed and the `CreateIndexOperation` is annotated with `DropExisting = true`.
+
+**IndexOptions:** When building the `WITH (...)` clause, `DROP_EXISTING = ON` is prepended to the options list when the `DropExisting` annotation is present.
+
+### `test/EFCore.SqlServer.FunctionalTests/Migrations/MigrationsSqlServerTest.cs`
+- Updated `Alter_index_make_unique` expected SQL: two-command DROP+CREATE → single `CREATE UNIQUE INDEX ... WITH (DROP_EXISTING = ON)`.
+- Updated `Alter_index_change_sort_order` expected SQL: two-command DROP+CREATE → single `CREATE INDEX ... WITH (DROP_EXISTING = ON)`.
+- Added `Alter_index_change_fill_factor` test that verifies changing only the fill factor of an existing index produces `CREATE INDEX ... WITH (DROP_EXISTING = ON, FILLFACTOR = 90)`.
+
+## Files Edited
+
+- `src/EFCore.SqlServer/Metadata/Internal/SqlServerAnnotationNames.cs`
+- `src/EFCore.SqlServer/Migrations/SqlServerMigrationsSqlGenerator.cs`
+- `test/EFCore.SqlServer.FunctionalTests/Migrations/MigrationsSqlServerTest.cs`
+
+## Precedent Usage
+
+**Query 1:** "SQL Server CREATE INDEX DROP_EXISTING ON instead of drop and recreate index migration"
+Result: BELOW THRESHOLD (score 0.415). Not useful — unrelated scaffolding PR.
+
+**Query 2:** "migrate index drop existing recreate SQL Server index annotation migration generator"
+Result: score 0.506, PR #37652 (full-text search catalog/index support). Useful for understanding how new index types are integrated (annotation names, generator dispatch, excluded from certain operations) but did not directly demonstrate the DROP_EXISTING pattern. The pattern of excluding special index types (full-text, vector) from standard DDL transformations was confirmed by examining this PR's approach.
+
+**Query 3:** "index rebuild migration SQL Server consolidate drop create single statement"
+Result: BELOW THRESHOLD (score 0.406). Not useful.
+
+Precedents were largely not applicable to this specific optimization; the implementation was derived directly from reading the existing code.
